          "body": "The chapter opens with the most sacred object in the Tabernacle and in all of Israel's subsequent history: the ark of the covenant and its lid, the mercy seat. The ark's design — acacia wood overlaid completely inside and out with pure gold — unites earthly and glorious materials in a single object. The mercy seat (*kapporet*, from *kaphar*, to atone or cover) is pure gold throughout: no wood core, no overlay, a single undivided mass of the most precious metal. This distinction matters: the container of the Law (the ark below) is covered with glory; the throne of atonement (the mercy seat above) IS glory. The two cherubim of hammered gold are formed as one piece with the mercy seat — not bolted on but integral. Their wings overshadow the mercy seat; their faces look down at it. On the Day of Atonement (Leviticus 16:14-15) the high priest sprinkled blood seven times before and on this very surface. The New Testament draws the line directly: Paul identifies Christ as the *hilasterion* — the mercy seat, the propitiation — in Romans 3:25. Hebrews 9:5 names the cherubim of glory over-shadowing it. The ark of Exodus 37 is the physical type; the cross of Christ is the antitype, the real atonement to which the annual blood-sprinkling pointed."
