          "body": "One of the chapter's most theologically significant details is the least visually dramatic: rings and poles appear on every piece of sacred furniture (vv. 3-5, 13-15, 27-28). The poles were never to be removed from the ark's rings (Exodus 25:15) — an instruction unique to the ark but paradigmatic for the whole furnishing system. These are not emergency carrying handles; they are permanent architectural features. This design element makes a statement: the God who dwells in the Tabernacle is not fixed to a location. He is not like the stationary cult idols of Egypt and Canaan, enthroned in stone temples. He accompanies His covenant people through wilderness, through Jordan crossing, through conquest and settlement. When the cloud moved, Israel moved, and the furniture moved with it (Numbers 9:15-23; 10:33-36). The poles on every piece of furniture are the material declaration of Immanuel — God with us, wherever the people go. The New Testament fulfillment is the incarnation itself: the Word pitched His tent (*eskēnōsen*) among us (John 1:14), bringing divine presence into human movement."
