          "body": "The lampstand (*menorah*) receives the most detailed description in the chapter (vv. 17-24), and its design is the most organic: cups shaped like almond blossoms, buds, and flowers distributed across seven branches, all of one piece, all hammered from a single talent of gold. The almond imagery is not decorative whimsy. The Hebrew *shaqed* (almond) shares its root with the verb *shoqed*, to watch or be wakeful — the wordplay God makes explicit in Jeremiah 1:11-12 when he shows Jeremiah an almond branch to declare, 'I am watching over My word to perform it.' The almond tree is the first to flower in Israel after winter dormancy, a sign of resurrection-life after apparent death. The lampstand therefore combines life, watchfulness, and light — and it provides the only illumination in the Holy Place. There is no window in the Holy Place; the priests minister entirely by lampstand light. This is the material truth the New Testament will crystallize: Christ is the light of the world (John 8:12; 9:5), and His people shine as lights in a dark world (Matthew 5:14-16; Philippians 2:15). Revelation 1:20 identifies the seven churches as seven lampstands, with Christ walking among them."
