          "body": "The chapter's final verse (37:29) is unlike every verse that precedes it: Bezalel does not make a piece of furniture but a compound — the holy anointing oil and the fragrant incense, 'the work of a perfumer.' These two substances will consecrate everything else. The anointing oil will be poured on the Tabernacle, the ark, the table, the lampstand, and the incense altar (Exodus 40:9-10), setting them apart as holy. Without the oil, the furniture is costly metalwork; with the oil, it is consecrated to God. The incense will fill the Holy Place with the fragrance of worship. Both are divinely specified in exact proportions (Exodus 30:23-25, 34-38) and are reserved exclusively for Tabernacle use — any person who replicates them for personal use is cut off from Israel (Exodus 30:32-33, 37-38). The anointing and the incense together establish that holiness is not a property objects possess inherently; it is a status God confers through prescribed means. The New Testament counterpart is the Holy Spirit who anoints and consecrates — it is He who takes the vessel of the believer and sets it apart for God's use (1 Corinthians 6:19-20; 2 Corinthians 1:21-22)."
